com.ebay.web.cors

Class CORSConfiguration

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.ebay.web.cors.CORSConfiguration

  • public final class CORSConfiguration
extends Object

    The configuration object for CORSFilter.

    • Allowed Origins: A Collection of origins consisting of zero or more origins that are allowed access to the resource. Init param name: cors.allowed.origins
    • Allowed HTTP Methods: A Collection of methods consisting of zero or more methods that are supported by the resource. Init param name: cors.allowed.methods
    • Allowed HTTP Headers: A Collection of headers consisting of zero or more header field names that are supported by the resource. Init param name: cors.allowed.headers
    • Exposed headers: A Collection of exposed headers consisting of zero or more header field names of headers other than the simple response headers that the resource might use and can be exposed. Init param name: cors.exposed.headers
    • Pre-flight max age: The amount of seconds the user agent is allowed to cache the result of the pre-flight request. Init param name: cors.preflight.maxage
    • Supports credentials: A supports credentials flag that indicates whether the resource supports user credentials in the request. It is true when the resource does and false otherwise. Init param name: cors.support.credentials

    If FilterConfig is not provided. Following defaults are used:

    • Allowed origin: *
    • Allowed HTTP methods: [GET, POST, OPTIONS, HEAD]
    • Pre-flight max age: 1800 seconds
    • Supports credentials: false
    • Allowed HTTP headers: Origin,Accept,X-Requested-With,Content-Type
    Author:
    Mohit Soni

        Initialize CORS configuration, by passing in configuration attributes from application.
        Parameters:
        allowedOrigins - A comma separated list of allowed origin for CORS.
        allowedHttpMethods - A comma separated list of allowed HTTP methods.
        allowedHttpHeaders - A comma separated list of allowed HTTP headers.
        exposedHeaders - A comma separated list of HTTP headers in response that we are XHR2 object can access.
        supportsCredentials - Is auth required ? Response will contain an allow credentials header.

        javax.servlet.ServletException
